    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nUnsure if this should be classified as a feature request or a bug. It's not strictly a bug, and more-so just a combination of features producing bad UX.\n\nWhen performing an action which variably opens the dialog window based on the height of the output (for example, `z=`, or a call to `vim.ui.select()`, the number of times to press `<Esc>` to cancel the action is variable. If the dialog window opens, it will be two times, otherwise it will be one. This is a bad user experience.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- `nvim --clean`\n- `:lua require('vim._core.ui2').enable()`\n- type `hi fsgjkfs`\n- Use `z=` on \"hi\". You will need to press `<Esc>` twice to cancel.\n- Use `z=` on \"fsgjkfs\". You will need to press `<Esc>` once to cancel.\n\nhi (dialog window opens, takes two presses of `<Esc>`):\n\n<img width=\"865\" height=\"561\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/826f3ee2-cfe6-4d7d-bb68-ea373ab5a0da\" />\n\nfsgjkfs (dialog window does not open, takes one press of `<Esc>`):\n\n<img width=\"865\" height=\"561\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a91cab3a-ca33-4b29-9c76-6c2f1324067c\" />\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIt always takes only one `<Esc>` to cancel a `vim.ui.select()`\n\n### Proposed Solution\n\nInstead of scrolling with the actual keys `f/d/j`, `b/u/k`, use the already established scrolling binds like `<C-u>`, `<C-d>`, `<S-Up>`, `<S-Down>`, `<C-b>`, `<C-f>`. This prevents the need to press `<Esc>` to exit this mode, so `<Esc>` can be bound to simply close the window, like in the msg window.\n\nThis would also be an alternative fix to #38481 which allows for bringing back the dialog window.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev+67-164dfa1d5",
